### Expected Cost and Mean-Variance

One of the most natural risk measures is represented directly by the _expected cost_ on the trajectories induced by a (hyper)policy. This "risk neutral" risk measure was introduced in Section 2 for both the PG exploration paradigms as \(J_{\text{AC},i}\) and \(J_{\text{PC},i}\), where \(i\) is the cost function index.

However, in some scenarios, it may be desirable to minimize jointly the expected cost and its variance. To this end, it is possible to consider the Mean-Variance (MV, Markowitz and Todd, 2000; Li and Ng, 2000) risk measure which models this kind of objective. Indeed, the MV is a combination of the mean cost and its variance over the trajectories. The MV with parameter \(\kappa\) over the random variable \(Z\), which represents a loss, is defined as follows:

\[\text{MV}_{\kappa}(Z):=\mathbb{E}\left[Z\right]+\kappa\,\mathbb{V}\mathrm{ar} \left[Z\right].\] (15)

### Chance Constraints, Value at Risk, and Conditional Value at Risk

Value at Risk (\(\text{VaR}_{\alpha}\)) and Conditional Value at Risk (\(\text{CVaR}_{\alpha}\)) are two popular and strongly connected risk measures. In the following, we report their standard definition as provided by Rockafellar and Uryasev (2000) and Chow et al. (2017).

\(\text{VaR}_{\alpha}\)measures risk as the maximum cost that might be incurred with respect to a given confidence level \(\alpha\in(0,1)\). Such a quantity models the _potential loss_ and the _probability_ that the loss will occur. In its classical definition, the \(\text{VaR}_{\alpha}\)is the worst-case loss associated with a probability and a time horizon. This risk metric is particularly useful when there is a well defined failure state. Formally:

\[\text{VaR}_{\alpha}(Z):=\min\left\{z|F_{Z}(z)\geq\alpha\right\}.\] (16)

\(\text{CVaR}_{\alpha}\)measures risk as the expected cost given that such cost is greater than or equal to \(\text{VaR}_{\alpha}\), and provides a number of theoretical and computational advantages. Such a quantity represents the _expected loss_ if the worst-case threshold is passed (i.e., beyond the \(\text{VaR}_{\alpha}\)breakpoint). Formally:

\[\text{CVaR}_{\alpha}(Z):=\min_{\eta\in\mathbb{R}}\left\{\eta+\frac{1}{1-\alpha }\,\mathbb{E}\left[(Z-\eta)^{+}\right]\right\}.\] (17)

Another risk measure, similar to the \(\text{VaR}_{\alpha}\)and the \(\text{CVaR}_{\alpha}\), is the _chance_ one. Considering _chance constraints_ means to consider constraints to hold with high probability. Indeed, constraints are imposed on the probability that the loss random variable exceeds a certain threshold \(n\):

\[\text{Chance}_{n}(Z):=\mathbb{P}(Z\geq n).\] (18)

### Unified Risk Measure Mapping

Here we introduce an objective for writing an optimization problem for different risk measures (Bisi et al., 2022). For every \(i\in\llbracket 0,U\rrbracket\), we introduce the functions \(f_{i}:\mathbb{R}^{2}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}\) and \(g_{i}:\mathbb{R}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}\) in order to express the unified risk-minimization objective function over a risk measure on \(C_{i}\) as:

\[\min_{\eta_{i}\in\mathbb{R}}\left\{\min_{\bm{\theta}\in\Theta}\underset{\tau \sim p_{\text{A}}(\cdot|\bm{\theta})}{\mathbb{E}}\left[f_{i}(C_{i}(\tau),\eta _{i})\right]+g_{i}(\eta_{i})\right\}.\] (19)

Thus, by fixing a policy parameter configuration \(\bm{\theta}\), we obtain an AB unified risk measure over \(C_{i}\) as follows:

\[\mathcal{Z}_{\text{A},i}(\bm{\theta}):=\min_{\eta_{i}\in\mathbb{R}}\left\{ \underset{\tau\sim p_{\text{A}}(\cdot|\bm{\theta})}{\mathbb{E}}\left[f_{i}(C_ {i}(\tau),\eta_{i})\right]+g_{i}(\eta_{i})\right\}.\] (20)

In order to switch to the PB exploration paradigm, we need to consider also the expectation over the parameter configuration of the underlying policy. Indeed, by fixing a hyperparameter configuration \(\bm{\rho}\), we can define:

\[\mathcal{Z}_{\text{P},i}(\bm{\rho}):=\min_{\eta_{i}\in\mathbb{R}}\left\{ \underset{\bm{\theta}\sim\bm{\nu}_{\rho}}{\mathbb{E}}\left[\underset{\tau \sim p_{\text{A}}(\cdot|\bm{\theta})}{\mathbb{E}}\left[f_{i}(C_{i}(\tau),\eta _{i})\right]\right]+g_{i}(\eta_{i})\right\}.\] (21)

By selecting the functions \(f_{i}\) and \(g_{i}\) we can consider distinct risk measures to minimize, as we show in Table 4.

The focus of this section is to derive the mapping between the functions \(f\) and \(g\) and the desired risk measure as shown in Table 4. In particular, we consider just the AB exploration scenario, since then passing to the PB one is straightforward. In this section, we consider a generic cost function \(c:\mathcal{S}\times\mathcal{A}\rightarrow\left[0,1\right]\) with its cumulative cost index over a trajectory \(\tau\) which is \(C(\tau)=\sum_{t=0}^{T-1}\gamma^{t}c(\bm{s}_{\tau,t},\bm{a}_{\tau,t})\). In what follows, with a little abuse of notation, we will write the risk measures with also a dependence on the policy parameters \(\bm{\theta}\) which induce trajectories \(\tau\).

Mean Cost.This is the simplest case, indeed, we can express the minimization problem of the mean cost as:

\[\min_{\bm{\theta}\in\Theta}\mathop{\mathbb{E}}_{\tau\sim p_{\Lambda}(\cdot| \bm{\theta})}\left[C(\tau)\right].\] (22)

Thus, it suffices to select \(f(C(\tau),\eta)=C(\tau)\) and \(g(\eta)=0\) to make the minimization problem fit with the form of the unified cost minimization formulation.

Conditional Value at Risk.For what concern the CVaR\({}_{\alpha}\), we can start from its formulation:

\[\min_{\bm{\theta}\in\Theta}\text{CVaR}_{\alpha}(\bm{\theta}) =\min_{\bm{\theta}\in\Theta}\left\{\min_{\eta\in\mathbb{R}} \left\{\eta+\frac{1}{1-\alpha}\mathop{\mathbb{E}}_{\tau\sim p_{\Lambda}(\cdot| \bm{\theta})}\left[\left(C(\tau)-\eta\right)^{+}\right]\right\}\right\}\] (23) \[=\min_{\eta\in\mathbb{R}}\left\{\eta+\min_{\bm{\theta}\in\Theta} \mathop{\mathbb{E}}_{\tau\sim p_{\Lambda}(\cdot|\bm{\theta})}\left[\frac{1}{1- \alpha}(C(\tau)-\eta)^{+}\right]\right\}.\] (24)

Thus, we need to select \(f(C(\tau),\eta)=\frac{1}{1-\alpha}(C(\tau)-\eta)^{+}\) and \(g(\eta)=\eta\) to complete the mapping to the unified cost minimization objective.

Mean Variance.For the MV\({}_{\kappa}(\bm{\theta})\) objective, we need to make some preliminary observations. In particular, for a generic finite-mean random variable \(X\), we have that:

\[\mathbb{V}\mathrm{ar}\left[X\right]=\mathbb{E}\left[X^{2}\right]-\mathbb{E} \left[X\right]^{2}.\] (25)

Moreover, by Fenchel duality, we have the following:

\[\mathbb{E}\left[X\right]^{2}=\max_{\eta\in\mathbb{R}}\left\{2\eta\,\mathbb{E }\left[X\right]-\eta^{2}\right\}.\] (26)

Given that, we can start the derivation from the minimization of the Mean Variance:

\[\min_{\bm{\theta}\in\Theta}\text{MV}_{\kappa}(C,\bm{\theta})\] (27) \[=\min_{\bm{\theta}\in\Theta}\left\{\mathop{\mathbb{E}}_{\tau\sim p _{\Lambda}(\cdot|\bm{\theta})}\left[C(\tau)\right]+\kappa\mathop{\mathbb{E}}_ {\tau\sim p_{\Lambda}(\cdot|\bm{\theta})}\left[C(\tau)^{2}\right]-\kappa \mathop{\mathbb{E}}_{\tau\sim p_{\Lambda}(\cdot|\bm{\theta})}\left[C(\tau) \right]^{2}\right\}\] (28) \[=\min_{\bm{\theta}\in\Theta}\left\{\mathop{\mathbb{E}}_{\tau\sim p _{\Lambda}(\cdot|\bm{\theta})}\left[C(\tau)\right]+\kappa\mathop{\mathbb{E}}_ {\tau\sim p_{\Lambda}(\cdot|\bm{\theta})}\left[C(\tau)^{2}\right]-\kappa \max_{\eta\in\mathbb{R}}\left\{2\eta\mathop{\mathbb{E}}_{\tau\sim p_{\Lambda }(\cdot|\bm{\theta})}\left[C(\tau)\right]-\eta^{2}\right\}\right\}\] (29) \[=\min_{\bm{\theta}\in\Theta}\left\{\mathop{\mathbb{E}}_{\tau\sim p _{\Lambda}(\cdot|\bm{\theta})}\left[C(\tau)\right]+\kappa\mathop{\mathbb{E}}_ {\tau\sim p_{\Lambda}(\cdot|\bm{\theta})}\left[C(\tau)^{2}\right]+\kappa\min_ {\eta\in\mathbb{R}}\left\{-2\eta\mathop{\mathbb{E}}_{\tau\sim p_{\Lambda}( \cdot|\bm{\theta})}\left[C(\tau)\right]+\eta^{2}\right\}\right\}\] (30) \[=\min_{\eta\in\mathbb{R}}\left\{\kappa\eta^{2}+\min_{\bm{\theta} \in\Theta}\left\{(1-2\kappa\eta)\mathop{\mathbb{E}}_{\tau\sim p_{\Lambda}( \cdot|\bm{\theta})}\left[C(\tau)\right]+\kappa\mathop{\mathbb{E}}_{\tau\sim p _{\Lambda}(\cdot|\bm{\theta})}\left[C(\tau)^{2}\right]\right\}\right\}.\] (31)

Thus, to complete the mapping, we need to select

\[f(C(\tau),\eta)=(1-2\kappa\eta)\mathop{\mathbb{E}}_{\tau\sim p_{\Lambda}(\cdot |\bm{\theta})}\left[C(\tau)\right]+\kappa\mathop{\mathbb{E}}_{\tau\sim p_{ \Lambda}(\cdot|\bm{\theta})}\left[C(\tau)^{2}\right]\]

and \(g(\eta)=\kappa\eta^{2}\).

Chance.For characterizing the chance constraints, we start by expressing the probability of an event \(A\) as the expected value of the indicator function:

\[\mathbb{P}\left(A\right)=\mathbb{E}\left[\mathbbm{1}\left\{A\right\}\right].\] (32)

Thus, having to minimize a chance measure on the cost with a parameter \(n\), we can rewrite it as:

\[\min_{\bm{\theta}\in\Theta}\text{Chance}_{n}(C,\bm{\theta}) =\min_{\bm{\theta}\in\Theta}\mathop{\mathbb{E}}_{\tau\sim p_{\Lambda }(\cdot|\bm{\theta})}\left[\mathbb{P}(C(\tau)\geq n)\right]\] (33) \[=\min_{\bm{\theta}\in\Theta}\mathop{\mathbb{E}}_{\tau\sim p_{ \Lambda}(\cdot|\bm{\theta})}\left[\mathbbm{1}\left\{C(\tau)\geq n\right\} \right].\] (34)Thus, to complete the mapping to the unified cost minimization objective, it suffices to select \(f(C(\tau),\eta)=1\left\{C(\tau)\geq n\right\}\) and \(g(\eta)=0\).

## Appendix D Estimators

Here, we provide all the explicit estimators' forms for both C-PGAE and C-PGPE and for each risk measure. For the sake of clarity, we report the mapping between the \(f_{i}\) and \(g_{i}\) functions and the risk measures in Table 4.

The general Lagrangian function for the problem in Equation (11) is the following:

\[\widetilde{\mathcal{L}}_{\uparrow,\omega}(\bm{\upsilon},\bm{\lambda},\bm{ \eta})\coloneqq\mathcal{J}_{\uparrow,0}(\bm{\upsilon},\eta_{0})+\sum_{u=1}^{ U}\lambda_{u}\left(\mathcal{J}_{\uparrow,u}(\bm{\upsilon},\eta_{u})-b_{u} \right)-\frac{\omega}{2}\left\|\bm{\lambda}\right\|_{2}^{2}.\] (35)

For what follows we are going to compute the following gradients:

1. \(\nabla_{\bm{\upsilon}}\widetilde{\mathcal{L}}_{\uparrow,\omega}(\bm{\upsilon },\bm{\lambda},\bm{\eta})\);
2. \(\nabla_{\bm{\lambda}}\widetilde{\mathcal{L}}_{\uparrow,\omega}(\bm{\upsilon },\bm{\lambda},\bm{\eta})\);
3. \(\nabla_{\bm{\eta}}\widetilde{\mathcal{L}}_{\uparrow,\omega}(\bm{\upsilon},\bm {\lambda},\bm{\eta})\).

Before entering into the details of the estimators, we show the general forms of the gradients of the Lagrangian.

General Gradient w.r.t. \(\bm{\upsilon}\).Notice that the following holds:

\[\nabla_{\bm{\upsilon}}\widetilde{\mathcal{L}}_{\uparrow,\omega}(\bm{\upsilon },\bm{\lambda},\bm{\eta})=\nabla_{\bm{\upsilon}}\mathcal{J}_{\uparrow,0}(\bm {\upsilon},\eta_{0})+\sum_{u=1}^{U}\lambda_{u}\nabla_{\bm{\upsilon}}\mathcal{ J}_{\uparrow,u}(\bm{\upsilon},\eta_{u}),\] (36)

thus, in what follows, for the gradient w.r.t. \(\bm{\upsilon}\) we focus on the single terms \(\nabla_{\bm{\upsilon}}\mathcal{J}_{\uparrow,u}(\bm{\upsilon},\eta_{u})\) for every \(u\in\llbracket 0,U\rrbracket\).

General Gradient w.r.t. \(\bm{\lambda}\).The general gradient w.r.t. \(\bm{\lambda}\) has the form:

\[\nabla_{\bm{\lambda}}\widetilde{\mathcal{L}}_{\uparrow,\omega}(\bm{\upsilon },\bm{\lambda},\bm{\eta})=\mathcal{J}_{\uparrow}(\bm{\upsilon},\bm{\eta})- \bm{b}+\omega\bm{\lambda},\] (37)

where \(\mathcal{J}_{\uparrow}(\bm{\upsilon},\bm{\eta})=\left(\mathcal{J}_{\uparrow,1 }(\bm{\upsilon},\eta_{1}),...,\mathcal{J}_{\uparrow,U}(\bm{\upsilon},\eta_{ U})\right)^{\top}\) and \(\bm{b}=\left(b_{1},...,b_{U}\right)^{\top}\).

General Gradient w.r.t. \(\bm{\eta}\).As done for the gradient w.r.t. \(\bm{\upsilon}\), the following holds:

\[\nabla_{\bm{\eta}}\widetilde{\mathcal{L}}_{\uparrow,\omega}(\bm{\upsilon},\bm {\lambda},\bm{\eta})=\nabla_{\bm{\eta}}\mathcal{J}_{\uparrow,0}(\bm{\upsilon },\eta_{0})+\sum_{u=1}^{U}\lambda_{u}\nabla_{\bm{\eta}}\mathcal{J}_{\uparrow,u }(\bm{\upsilon},\eta_{u}).\] (38)

Thus, also in this case, we will focus on the single terms \(\nabla_{\bm{\eta}}\mathcal{J}_{\uparrow,u}(\bm{\upsilon},\eta_{u})\) for every \(u\in\llbracket 0,U\rrbracket\).

